dataset_description.json.Name: OLVSL_ Object-location visual statistical learning
dataset_description.json.Description: This study examined incidental learning of probabilistic contingencies between spatial locations and object identities. On each trial, participants were presented with one of four possible colourful shapes, and were required to identify the target via button-press as quickly and accurately as possible. The target could appear in one of four locations - one in each of the four quadrants of the visual field. Each location was associated with one shape that appeared there frequently and one shape that appeared there infrequently; a second location was associated with the same targets, but with the opposite contingency mapping. Each trial had a single target that was thus either likely at the cued location (Frequent target condition), or unlikely at the cued location (Infrequent target condition).

README:
This dataset was obtained from the OpenfMRI project (http://www.openfmri.org)
Description: Object-location incidental learning.
These data correspond to Experiment 2 in Hall, Naughtin, Mattingley, & Dux, (in press). Distributed and opposing effects of incidental learning in the human brain. NeuroImage.

Missing data
--------
No scanning data for sub-02 run-10: technical issues during scanning
No scanning data for sub-08 run-10: technical issues during scanning
No scanning data for sub-15 run-01: technical issues during scanning
Scanning data excluded for sub-16 run-10: excessive motion in the scanner
No scanning data for sub-21 run-01 & run-02: technical issues during scanning
	
Source data processing
--------
dicomrename was used in MATLAB 2015b to collate and rename Siemens IMA files. Code is available at https://mathworks.com/matlabcentral/fileexchange/22818-dicomrename
dcm2niix was used to convert DICOM files to NIFTI format. Code is available at https://github.com/rordenlab/dcm2niix
jq was used to edit json files. Code is available at https://stedolan.github.io/jq/
Custom code implemented in MATLAB 2015b was used to extract data for event logs.

Defacing
--------
mri_deface was used on all anatomical images to ensure deindentification of subjects. Code is available at https://surfer.nmr.mgh.harvard.edu/fswiki/mri_deface
